The dtype and shape information for resource arguments has to be handled
specially: GraphDef encodes that information in _handle_dtypes and
_handle_shapes attributes while MLIR encodes that information using
!tf.resource subtypes.

When exporting MLIR to GraphDef, add _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes for resource arguments. This is consistent with import, which
already has a special case for reading the _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes on import from GraphDef to MLIR.

This fixes RET_CHECK arg_shape.handle_type != DT_INVALID errors that happen
when converting GraphDef to and from MLIR before passing the graph to the old
TF/XLA bridge.

The dtype and shape information for resource arguments has to be handled
specially: GraphDef encodes that information in _handle_dtypes and
_handle_shapes attributes while MLIR encodes that information using
!tf.resource subtypes.

When exporting MLIR to GraphDef, add _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes for resource arguments. This is consistent with import, which
already has a special case for reading the _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes on import from GraphDef to MLIR.

This fixes RET_CHECK arg_shape.handle_type != DT_INVALID errors that happen
when converting GraphDef to and from MLIR before passing the graph to the old
TF/XLA bridge.

Hameed","email":"1b4ea0cc3b7e92e1b63958403a4b855ff79112a7@gmail.com"},"message":"lite: nnapi: Check memory mapping errors after NNMemory()

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`) in
the constructor.

Ideally, one should check for errors early. However, since Google's C++
style guide prohibits the use of exceptions, we need to check this
explicitly after the constructor instead. We check `NNMemory::data_ptr_`
for any errors (since `NNMemory::fd_` is private).

Signed-off-by: Waqar Hameed <whame91@gmail.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheAssassinRen/tensorflow/commits/9f5e38b536e0cfa239e53fb57bf6789d7a5f9ad0"},{"sha":"43228ce61100811f208aaa61e70592931017f3a7","author":{"name":"Yair Ehrenwald","email":"419dcca5709679f19437d0546fb4c17eb1f0f73c@ceva-dsp.com"},"message":"Added optimized quantize kernel","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheAssassinRen/tensorflow/commits/43228ce61100811f208aaa61e70592931017f3a7"},{"sha":"f2e5a130cb2a42b507f6be718dc4c6d3ec305a10","author":{"name":"Yair Ehrenwald","email":"419dcca5709679f19437d0546fb4c17eb1f0f73c@ceva-dsp.com"},"message":"Merge remote-tracking branch 'upstream/master' into add_quantize_optimized","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheAssassinRen/tensorflow/commits/f2e5a130cb2a42b507f6be718dc4c6d3ec305a10"}]

The dtype and shape information for resource arguments has to be handled
specially: GraphDef encodes that information in _handle_dtypes and
_handle_shapes attributes while MLIR encodes that information using
!tf.resource subtypes.

When exporting MLIR to GraphDef, add _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes for resource arguments. This is consistent with import, which
already has a special case for reading the _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes on import from GraphDef to MLIR.

This fixes RET_CHECK arg_shape.handle_type != DT_INVALID errors that happen
when converting GraphDef to and from MLIR before passing the graph to the old
TF/XLA bridge.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 363948229
Change-Id: Id8b45da0979addc953c147189ee3abf23594a1f0","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/waterdrops/tensorflow/commits/d58a39730d73f7076cdae020da6a4a8954f1d3f4"},{"sha":"0ae1a36ee0e5002c73555af83717ef142aade5e5","author":{"name":"Richard Uhler","email":"394366297491d0a7105f27d2861637ec705af27e@google.com"},"message":"Add _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes attributes on export.

The dtype and shape information for resource arguments has to be handled
specially: GraphDef encodes that information in _handle_dtypes and
_handle_shapes attributes while MLIR encodes that information using
!tf.resource subtypes.

When exporting MLIR to GraphDef, add _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes for resource arguments. This is consistent with import, which
already has a special case for reading the _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes on import from GraphDef to MLIR.

This fixes RET_CHECK arg_shape.handle_type != DT_INVALID errors that happen
when converting GraphDef to and from MLIR before passing the graph to the old
TF/XLA bridge.

Change-Id: Id8b45da0979addc953c147189ee3abf23594a1f0","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedforgood/tensorflow/commits/d58a39730d73f7076cdae020da6a4a8954f1d3f4"},{"sha":"0ae1a36ee0e5002c73555af83717ef142aade5e5","author":{"name":"Richard Uhler","email":"394366297491d0a7105f27d2861637ec705af27e@google.com"},"message":"Add _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes attributes on export.

The dtype and shape information for resource arguments has to be handled
specially: GraphDef encodes that information in _handle_dtypes and
_handle_shapes attributes while MLIR encodes that information using
!tf.resource subtypes.

When exporting MLIR to GraphDef, add _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes for resource arguments. This is consistent with import, which
already has a special case for reading the _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes on import from GraphDef to MLIR.

This fixes RET_CHECK arg_shape.handle_type != DT_INVALID errors that happen
when converting GraphDef to and from MLIR before passing the graph to the old
TF/XLA bridge.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 363948229
Change-Id: Id8b45da0979addc953c147189ee3abf23594a1f0","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/d58a39730d73f7076cdae020da6a4a8954f1d3f4"},{"sha":"0ae1a36ee0e5002c73555af83717ef142aade5e5","author":{"name":"Richard Uhler","email":"394366297491d0a7105f27d2861637ec705af27e@google.com"},"message":"Add _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes attributes on export.

The dtype and shape information for resource arguments has to be handled
specially: GraphDef encodes that information in _handle_dtypes and
_handle_shapes attributes while MLIR encodes that information using
!tf.resource subtypes.

When exporting MLIR to GraphDef, add _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes for resource arguments. This is consistent with import, which
already has a special case for reading the _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes on import from GraphDef to MLIR.

This fixes RET_CHECK arg_shape.handle_type != DT_INVALID errors that happen
when converting GraphDef to and from MLIR before passing the graph to the old
TF/XLA bridge.

Hameed","email":"1b4ea0cc3b7e92e1b63958403a4b855ff79112a7@gmail.com"},"message":"lite: nnapi: Check memory mapping errors after NNMemory()

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`) in
the constructor.

Ideally, one should check for errors early. However, since Google's C++
style guide prohibits the use of exceptions, we need to check this
explicitly after the constructor instead. We check `NNMemory::data_ptr_`
for any errors (since `NNMemory::fd_` is private).

Signed-off-by: Waqar Hameed <whame91@gmail.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/9f5e38b536e0cfa239e53fb57bf6789d7a5f9ad0"},{"sha":"de458674ec2dc81dde147e6fbf4347d260cdddfd","author":{"name":"Duncan Riach","email":"f69bf5514fde50d7fb64e12e8052d5aebfc37e06@nvidia.com"},"message":"[determinism] Add segment reduction op exceptions","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/de458674ec2dc81dde147e6fbf4347d260cdddfd"}]

We added this unstable feature a few years ago, as a way to opt out of
context updates, but it didn't prove useful in practice.

We have other proposals for how to address the same problem, like
context selectors.

Since it was prefixed with `unstable_`, we should be able to remove it
without consequence. The hook API already warned if you used it.

Even if someone is using it somewhere, it's meant to be an optimization
only, so if they are using the API properly, it should not have any
semantic impact.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/zys-contrib/react/commits/6d3ecb70dceb225af0cd990b46d6c44b852c1d82"}]

We don't need this anymore. It only existed so we could cancel the
callback later. But canceling isn't necessary, was only an
"optimization" for something that almost never happens in practice.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/chanhong/react/commits/754e307284d5b4de32da1bd64c179885f6d9f253"},{"sha":"6d3ecb70dceb225af0cd990b46d6c44b852c1d82","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Remove unstable_changedBits (#20953)

We added this unstable feature a few years ago, as a way to opt out of
context updates, but it didn't prove useful in practice.

We have other proposals for how to address the same problem, like
context selectors.

Since it was prefixed with `unstable_`, we should be able to remove it
without consequence. The hook API already warned if you used it.

Even if someone is using it somewhere, it's meant to be an optimization
only, so if they are using the API properly, it should not have any

The "userxattr" option is needed for mounting overlayfs inside a user namespace with kernel >= 5.11.

The "userxattr" option is NOT needed for the initial user namespace (aka "the host").

Also, Ubuntu (since circa 2015) and Debian (since 10) with kernel < 5.11 can mount the overlayfs in a user namespace without the "userxattr" option.

The corresponding kernel commit: 2d2f2d7322ff43e0fe92bf8cccdc0b09449bf2e1
> **ovl: user xattr**
>
> Optionally allow using "user.overlay." namespace instead of "trusted.overlay."
> ...
> Disable redirect_dir and metacopy options, because these would allow privilege escalation through direct manipulation of the
> "user.overlay.redirect" or "user.overlay.metacopy" xattrs.

Fix issue 42055

Related to containerd/containerd PR 5076

This seems to be testing a strange case, specifically that one can set
the `--net` and `--network` in the same command with the same network.

Indeed this used to work with older CLIs but newer ones error out when
validating the request before sending it to the daemon.

Opening this for discussion because:

1. This doesn't seem to be testing anything at all related to the rest
   of the test
2. Not really providing any value here.
3. Is testing that a technically invalid option is successful (whether
   the option should be valid as it relates to the CLI accepting it is
   debatable).
4. Such a case seems fringe and even a bug in whatever is calling the
   CLI with such options.

Tonis mentioned that we can run into issues if there is more error
handling added here. This adds a custom reader implementation which is
like io.MultiReader except it does not cache EOF's.
What got us into trouble in the first place is `io.MultiReader` will
always return EOF once it has received an EOF, however the error
handling that we are going for is to recover from an EOF because the
underlying file is a file which can have more data added to it after
EOF.

[{"sha":"cb501700e809f75abe858fa6c68cf24915bc5c01","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix handling for json-file io.UnexpectedEOF

When the multireader hits EOF, we will always get EOF from it, so we
cannot store the multrireader fro later error handling, only for the
decoder.

Thanks @tobiasstadler for pointing this error out.

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>
(cherry picked from commit 4be98a38e7810940c260d778cfe128b97d9245fb)
Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/moby/moby/commits/cb501700e809f75abe858fa6c68cf24915bc5c01"},{"sha":"969bde20097d54c5ab2534c1e8a9e39cf7844722","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"jsonfile: more defensive reader implementation

Tonis mentioned that we can run into issues if there is more error
handling added here. This adds a custom reader implementation which is
like io.MultiReader except it does not cache EOF's.
What got us into trouble in the first place is `io.MultiReader` will
always return EOF once it has received an EOF, however the error
handling that we are going for is to recover from an EOF because the
underlying file is a file which can have more data added to it after
EOF.

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>
(cherry picked from commit 5a664dc87d79ddc9f09c7a963c52f491999dc939)

Signed-off-by: Kevin Cheng <kevin.cheng@arm.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/freedomtan/tensorflow/commits/dd5056ca09d1a0765b0f3adf308cbb2d40b18dc9"},{"sha":"d4dffb1c29ba27bb0859fe5547b00404069ffad4","author":{"name":"Mehdi Amini","email":"808100943be7b7010123d78912f654820a5ee1c1@google.com"},"message":"Introduce a `RefineTypeWith` method in shape_inference (NFC)

This method takes two TensorFlow types and tries to produce a more refined
type, where "refine" implies that more static information are known about
it.
This patch is NFC, the new method is introduced and correctness checked by
changing the implementation of `CanRefineTypeWith` to use this new method.
A future patch will refactor the uses of CanRefineTypeWith to use this in

PiperOrigin-RevId: 361234109
Change-Id: I5a89b41f600d6e03c75366fb41e1b5fdbefe9f1a","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/freedomtan/tensorflow/commits/de5bfc8bb62ee0b73f0d84e9f7f37b83475f4371"},{"sha":"0029a3c377e9e0e05d6a381dda1ac418f4357e9f","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Fix bug when LossScaleOptimizer and gradient_aggregator were used.

Before, if there were multiple processes each with a LossScaleOptimizer, and the inner optimizer had a custom gradient_aggregator to aggregate gradients across the processes, the LossScaleOptimizers in the processes could become out of sync. In particular, if a strict subset of replicas encountered NaN gradients, only the LossScaleOptimizers with NaN gradients would skip the step, while the LossScaleOptimizers with finite gradients would still apply gradients

Resolves https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues/46863. Horovod was broken with LossScaleOptimizer in TF 2.4 due to this bug, but they patched in a workaround. With this fix, the workaround will not be necessary in TF 2.5.

The issue was caused by the fact the gradients were checked for NaNs before they were all-reduced. This was handled correctly with tf.distribute.Strategy but not with an arbitrary gradient_aggregator. Now, the gradients are all-reduced before they are checked for NaNs, which means if any replica has NaNs, they all will have NaNs.

This potentially will allow better performance in the future as well, as it allows earlier-computed gradients to be all-reduced in parallel with the computation of later-computed gradients.

context updates, but it didn't prove useful in practice.

We have other proposals for how to address the same problem, like
context selectors.

Since it was prefixed with `unstable_`, we should be able to remove it
without consequence. The hook API already warned if you used it.

Even if someone is using it somewhere, it's meant to be an optimization
only, so if they are using the API properly, it should not have any
semantic impact.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/SimenB/react/commits/6d3ecb70dceb225af0cd990b46d6c44b852c1d82"}]

callback later. But canceling isn't necessary, was only an

We added this unstable feature a few years ago, as a way to opt out of
context updates, but it didn't prove useful in practice.

We have other proposals for how to address the same problem, like
context selectors.

Since it was prefixed with `unstable_`, we should be able to remove it
without consequence. The hook API already warned if you used it.

Even if someone is using it somewhere, it's meant to be an optimization
only, so if they are using the API properly, it should not have any
semantic impact.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/chojar/react/commits/6d3ecb70dceb225af0cd990b46d6c44b852c1d82"}]

[{"sha":"fd4bbe42ab3fdd2b2658fe214bf02c9546a2f1e7","author":{"name":"Ilya Lobkov","email":"85c2ea967b105e794f3d6357820cb3c03b0bc908@konghq.com"},"message":"feat(kuma-cp) extend CircuitBreaker (#1655)","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kumahq/kuma/commits/fd4bbe42ab3fdd2b2658fe214bf02c9546a2f1e7"},{"sha":"1cd6a224600a3989e6aa560cce7fdc900f869a99","author":{"name":"Bart Smykla","email":"1510bcc82b444bd3d94fed33ba1fa2e72fc0e429@smykla.com"},"message":"feat(ci/cd) wait for check before e2e/integration (#1690)

As `check` is running in parallel with `build/images` jobs,
and according to my experience looking at some of the last CI/CD
runs `build/images` is taking slightly more time than the `check`
itself, so it doesn't make sense if the only expectation from
not `requiring` it before running `e2e`-related jobs was to speed
it up.

What we are gaining by waiting for `check` to finish is much
quicker feedback when we forgot to run `make check` before pushing
new changes. It's not very rare to happen and without this
requirement, even if `check` fails, the whole spectrum of heavy
e2e tests will still run without a need, as we will have to still
run it again with the `make check` results.

Of course we can manually cancel that kind of job, but to achieve
this we would have to be always present at CircleCI console.

It has significant impact when we are beginning to introduce tests
which are run on automatically created infrastructure (i.e. EKS)
as it introduces real and unnecessary costs.

From my observations, the last CI/CD run times were:
- build (1m 20s) + images (3m 5s) = 4m 25s
- check = 2m 39s

[{"sha":"be5a2e231ae27b2c64806c026a5b9921be5e7560","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Land enableSyncMicrotasks (#20979)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Muhammadariesta/react/commits/be5a2e231ae27b2c64806c026a5b9921be5e7560"},{"sha":"754e307284d5b4de32da1bd64c179885f6d9f253","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Delete immediateQueueCallbackNode (#20980)

We don't need this anymore. It only existed so we could cancel the
callback later. But canceling isn't necessary, was only an
"optimization" for something that almost never happens in practice.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Muhammadariesta/react/commits/754e307284d5b4de32da1bd64c179885f6d9f253"},{"sha":"6d3ecb70dceb225af0cd990b46d6c44b852c1d82","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Remove unstable_changedBits (#20953)

We added this unstable feature a few years ago, as a way to opt out of
context updates, but it didn't prove useful in practice.

We have other proposals for how to address the same problem, like
context selectors.

Since it was prefixed with `unstable_`, we should be able to remove it
without consequence. The hook API already warned if you used it.

Even if someone is using it somewhere, it's meant to be an optimization
only, so if they are using the API properly, it should not have any
semantic impact.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Muhammadariesta/react/commits/6d3ecb70dceb225af0cd990b46d6c44b852c1d82"}]

We added this unstable feature a few years ago, as a way to opt out of
context updates, but it didn't prove useful in practice.

We have other proposals for how to address the same problem, like
context selectors.

Since it was prefixed with `unstable_`, we should be able to remove it
without consequence. The hook API already warned if you used it.

Even if someone is using it somewhere, it's meant to be an optimization
only, so if they are using the API properly, it should not have any
semantic impact.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MichaelDeBoey/react/commits/6d3ecb70dceb225af0cd990b46d6c44b852c1d82"}]

We added this unstable feature a few years ago, as a way to opt out of
context updates, but it didn't prove useful in practice.

context selectors.

Since it was prefixed with `unstable_`, we should be able to remove it
without consequence. The hook API already warned if you used it.

only, so if they are using the API properly, it should not have any

[{"sha":"3aa7ea52887095f4e535f06cafbfd522951fbd14","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Detach sibling pointers in old child list

When a fiber is deleted, it's still part of the previous (alternate)
parent fiber's list of children. Because children are a linked list, an
earlier sibling that's still alive will be connected to the deleted
fiber via its alternate:


  live fiber
  --alternate--> previous live fiber
  --sibling--> deleted fiber

We can't disconnect `alternate` on nodes that haven't been deleted
yet, but we can disconnect the `sibling` and `child` pointers.

Will use this feature flag to test the memory impact.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/3aa7ea52887095f4e535f06cafbfd522951fbd14"}]

[{"sha":"95d2b686bee0370719991fa78edce77f21fff11b","author":{"name":"Akihiro Suda","email":"10ddef0dea2a66ab193b07198faa879adcb213d8@hco.ntt.co.jp"},"message":"overlay2: support "userxattr" option (kernel 5.11)

The "userxattr" option is needed for mounting overlayfs inside a user namespace with kernel >= 5.11.

The "userxattr" option is NOT needed for the initial user namespace (aka "the host").

Also, Ubuntu (since circa 2015) and Debian (since 10) with kernel < 5.11 can mount the overlayfs in a user namespace without the "userxattr" option.

The corresponding kernel commit: 2d2f2d7322ff43e0fe92bf8cccdc0b09449bf2e1
> **ovl: user xattr**
>
> Optionally allow using "user.overlay." namespace instead of "trusted.overlay."
> ...
> Disable redirect_dir and metacopy options, because these would allow privilege escalation through direct manipulation of the
> "user.overlay.redirect" or "user.overlay.metacopy" xattrs.

Fix issue 42055

Related to containerd/containerd PR 5076

[{"sha":"8066dbe5c2b1687359ee84ca6cfab685536e47cc","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Detach sibling pointers in old child list

When a fiber is deleted, it's still part of the previous (alternate)
parent fiber's list of children. Because children are a linked list, an
earlier sibling that's still alive will be connected to the deleted
fiber via its alternate:


  live fiber
  --alternate--> previous live fiber
  --sibling--> deleted fiber

We can't disconnect `alternate` on nodes that haven't been deleted
yet, but we can disconnect the `sibling` and `child` pointers.

Will use this feature flag to test the memory impact.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/8066dbe5c2b1687359ee84ca6cfab685536e47cc"}]

[{"sha":"cd48a06547390ae426a70d555ec9fd5349c85d08","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Set up infra for react-reconciler fork (#18285)

* ReactFiberReconciler -> ReactFiberReconciler.old

* Set up infra for react-reconciler fork

We're planning to land some significant refactors of the reconciler.
We want to be able to gradually roll out the new implementation side-by-
side with the existing one. So we'll create a short lived fork of the
react-reconciler package. Once the new implementation has stabilized,
we'll delete the old implementation and promote the new one.

This means, for as long as the fork exists, we'll need to maintain two
separate implementations. This sounds painful, but since the forks will
still be largely the same, most changes will not require two separate
implementations. In practice, you'll implement the change in the old
fork and then copy paste it to the new one.

This commit only sets up the build and testing infrastructure. It does
not actually fork any modules. I'll do that in subsequent PRs.

The forked version of the reconciler will be used to build a special
version of React DOM. I've called this build ReactDOMForked. It's only
built for www; there's no open source version.

The new reconciler is disabled by default. It's enabled in the
`yarn test-www-variant` command. The reconciler fork isn't really
related to the "variant" feature of the www builds, but I'm piggy
backing on that concept to avoid having to add yet another
testing dimension.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bgirard/react/commits/cd48a06547390ae426a70d555ec9fd5349c85d08"},{"sha":"d3ec42020d220777bf589bec36c9cd8300ec9742","author":{"name":"Dominic Gannaway","email":"f36081f344c7ddccdaf04c4393ad3afe1eae700e@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Address feedback for accumulateTwoPhaseListeners (#18289)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bgirard/react/commits/d3ec42020d220777bf589bec36c9cd8300ec9742"},{"sha":"2a7cd589567b6a6fdb38664565bfad7ba3f14b6b","author":{"name":"Dominic Gannaway","email":"f36081f344c7ddccdaf04c4393ad3afe1eae700e@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"ReactDOM.useEvent: Add DOM host event listener logic (#18292)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bgirard/react/commits/2a7cd589567b6a6fdb38664565bfad7ba3f14b6b"},{"sha":"885ed469096d4da7ca038564b323e9b706f5a6d0","author":{"name":"wittgenst","email":"8f12a8a773c039ecbb285145e80048ddd454afd9@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Move MS Windows build to CircleCI (#17984)

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"PR #47767: lite: nnapi: Check memory mapping errors after NNMemory()

Imported from GitHub PR https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/47767

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`)...

Change-Id: Id8b45da0979addc953c147189ee3abf23594a1f0","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/melG81/tensorflow/commits/d58a39730d73f7076cdae020da6a4a8954f1d3f4"},{"sha":"0ae1a36ee0e5002c73555af83717ef142aade5e5","author":{"name":"Richard Uhler","email":"394366297491d0a7105f27d2861637ec705af27e@google.com"},"message":"Add _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes attributes on export.

The dtype and shape information for resource arguments has to be handled
specially: GraphDef encodes that information in _handle_dtypes and
_handle_shapes attributes while MLIR encodes that information using
!tf.resource subtypes.

When exporting MLIR to GraphDef, add _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes for resource arguments. This is consistent with import, which
already has a special case for reading the _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes on import from GraphDef to MLIR.

This fixes RET_CHECK arg_shape.handle_type != DT_INVALID errors that happen
when converting GraphDef to and from MLIR before passing the graph to the old
TF/XLA bridge.

Change-Id: Id8b45da0979addc953c147189ee3abf23594a1f0","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/tensorflow/commits/d58a39730d73f7076cdae020da6a4a8954f1d3f4"},{"sha":"0ae1a36ee0e5002c73555af83717ef142aade5e5","author":{"name":"Richard Uhler","email":"394366297491d0a7105f27d2861637ec705af27e@google.com"},"message":"Add _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes attributes on export.

The dtype and shape information for resource arguments has to be handled
specially: GraphDef encodes that information in _handle_dtypes and
_handle_shapes attributes while MLIR encodes that information using
!tf.resource subtypes.

When exporting MLIR to GraphDef, add _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes for resource arguments. This is consistent with import, which
already has a special case for reading the _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes on import from GraphDef to MLIR.

This fixes RET_CHECK arg_shape.handle_type != DT_INVALID errors that happen
when converting GraphDef to and from MLIR before passing the graph to the old
TF/XLA bridge.

[{"sha":"9780942e203b09fc4789ff5c426549baf7d242a3","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Remove cli test for duplicate --net/--network opts

This seems to be testing a strange case, specifically that one can set
the `--net` and `--network` in the same command with the same network.

Indeed this used to work with older CLIs but newer ones error out when
validating the request before sending it to the daemon.

Opening this for discussion because:

1. This doesn't seem to be testing anything at all related to the rest
   of the test
2. Not really providing any value here.
3. Is testing that a technically invalid option is successful (whether
   the option should be valid as it relates to the CLI accepting it is
   debatable).
4. Such a case seems fringe and even a bug in whatever is calling the
   CLI with such options.

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>
(cherry picked from commit e31086320ea0305e2cc70490160ee30480471680)

This makes tf-opt more strict on the dialect dependencies, and immediately reduces
the number of dialects loaded.

were dominated the time, which is unexpected since Linalg is not even intended to be
used there.

[{"sha":"d1d9f7d8eff3474233b00e8a99395cc148d357d8","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Detach sibling pointers in old child list

When a fiber is deleted, it's still part of the previous (alternate)
parent fiber's list of children. Because children are a linked list, an
earlier sibling that's still alive will be connected to the deleted
fiber via its alternate:


  live fiber
  --alternate--> previous live fiber
  --sibling--> deleted fiber

We can't disconnect `alternate` on nodes that haven't been deleted
yet, but we can disconnect the `sibling` and `child` pointers.

Will use this feature flag to test the memory impact.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/d1d9f7d8eff3474233b00e8a99395cc148d357d8"}]

Hameed","email":"1b4ea0cc3b7e92e1b63958403a4b855ff79112a7@gmail.com"},"message":"lite: nnapi: Check memory mapping errors after NNMemory()

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`) in
the constructor.

Ideally, one should check for errors early. However, since Google's C++
style guide prohibits the use of exceptions, we need to check this
explicitly after the constructor instead. We check `NNMemory::data_ptr_`
for any errors (since `NNMemory::fd_` is private).

Signed-off-by: Waqar Hameed <whame91@gmail.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/9f5e38b536e0cfa239e53fb57bf6789d7a5f9ad0"},{"sha":"de458674ec2dc81dde147e6fbf4347d260cdddfd","author":{"name":"Duncan Riach","email":"f69bf5514fde50d7fb64e12e8052d5aebfc37e06@nvidia.com"},"message":"[determinism] Add segment reduction op exceptions","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/de458674ec2dc81dde147e6fbf4347d260cdddfd"}]
